,Not Recommended,230050,19740484,"Posted: 16 December, 2015",all,iN008,"DLC Quest is a simplistic satire game about DLC. Sadly this joke gets old after 15 minutes ad one would probably expect. After all transforming a joke into a game doesn't improve the quality of the joke; rather in this case, transform said joke into meaningless blabber that comes off as repetitive and obnoxious. Gameplay itself is lacklustre and generally shoddy. As for graphics, well retro graphics are no excuse for unimaginative and ugly design. We've seen many games use retro style successfully: Hotline Miami, Evoland, and Cave Story to name a few, yet DLC Quest fails to hit the mark. Perhaps the only redeemable aspect is it's chip-tune music.Had I reviewed this game years ago upon first playing it, I would have given it a positive review, but upon looking back, a mixed-negative review is far more appropriate."
76561198041940756,Recommended,230050,22754236,"Posted: 1 May, 2016",all,RedGryphon0,Pretty decent for a meme game. Worth a dollar or so if you can catch it on sale.7/10 depends on you sense of humor really.
76561198030080447,Recommended,230050,11169828,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,PrinzEugen,"Extremely funny pun at the DLC-habitsThis is a very funny, small, but well-made and well thought-off game. It's essentially a sidescrolling platformer, with some jumping action and minor skills required (a gamepad comes in handy). Graphics and sound are minimalistic, even quite retro (I was reminded of the games of the 80's). But this serves a purpose: to make fun of the ever-growing DLC-habits (and sometimes misuse) in the games of, let's say, the last five years.So you start the game literally without anything. You can hardly move your character, there is no sound, even no menu. All of these have to be purchased as dlc-packs, to be paid for with in-game found gold. It's a simple but original idea, and it's very well executed, with lots of humour. I found myself laughing out aloud quite often. There is even a totally non-important sequel, so the sequelitis also gets a slap at.That's all there is to it, really. The game is original, funny, and - despite the tons of dlc's - very short. But for very little money, do try it, and treat yourself on some great moments. It even has Steam-acievements (which are also made fun of!) and Steam trading cards, so for badge-hunters this is a real treat.Gameplay: 21/30 (the basic idea gets done well, but that's it)Graphics: 10/20Sound: 6/10 (I liked the retro sounds)Replayability &long-lasting appeal: 10/20 (it's very short, but it's cheap too)Stability/patching: 18/20 (no issues whatsoever)Final score: 65/100"
