76561198123412640,Recommended,230050,15316416,"Posted: 11 April, 2015",all,Sam Lilly,"DLC Quest is a satirical 2D platformer that uses a retro aesthetic to poke fun at modern conventions. You start out only being able to move right. You need to unlock and purchase your way through the game via downloadable content. Don't worry, you use in-game coins to purchase the packs. You need to buy things as basic as sound, animation, and free movement as well as new abilities and cosmetic changes. I'd go into more detail, but explaining the joke would ruin the experience for you. Just know there are some very clever bit of DLC and dialogue that do a good job exaggerating the ridiculous nature of many greedy modern games. The basic plot is to save the princess in the first episode, and to save the town in the second. Most of the achievements are simple, requiring you to simply go through the quest. You can collect all the coins, find and purchase all the DLC packs, and beat the game. There are a few more difficult ones, such as the speedrunning achievements, if you're looking for replay and challenge. I like the music, the art, and the humor. It's a fun little game, but it does have a few problems.One problem with this game is that it's short. It has a lot of clever things to experience and a decent sized world, especially with the two combined campaigns, but it's still only going to take, at most, a few hours to beat. Also, while the humor hit me well, it may not be for everyone. That, and the fact that after you go through the game and get all the jokes, you're left with just the gameplay experience. This is a bit of a problem because, while it is a good experience as a whole, if the humor gets old then you're left with a short and very easy game. It coasts on the satire, perhaps to a fault. I'd like to see a larger game with this style because the controls, art, and music were all good... but this isn't going to be one you want to replay tons of times unless you're a speed runner. Also, I would've liked more music themes in the game, but the ones that are there are very catchy so I can give that a pass.Overall, DLC Quest a pretty fun little game that makes fun of ridiculous practices in modern games. If you like classic games, satire, and simple fun then you'll probably enjoy this little experience. I feel it has enough here to be worth the 3 dollar asking price, but if you're on the fence about it, just know that it does seem to go on sale now and then for less. It you want have a little fun with a retro style game that pokes some fun at newer ones, this is for you. Here's hoping we get more games with this nice kind of control and level design in the future. DLC Quest get a 6/10 for being a rather shallow game that makes up for its shortcomings in very clever design humor."
76561198206589356,Recommended,230050,15459287,"Posted: 19 April, 2015",all,The Yellow Flash,"Despite being a parody of the current generation of games, it is actually a (Short) game done right.It also doesn’t hurt that it was clearly made by a person that understood  how to make games.The only problem with the game is that it is too short (about half an hour) and could do with a sequel.Which would also play a part of the theme.Which it does have included as a special Game of the Year Edition extra. The included sequel is a lot longer and harder and just like the first one has two endings (or more), which plays out as two different games.Its a great game to play if your waiting to play other games or just want something quick that’s built like other games with pretty much no problems at all. Its short so little progress is not a big issue like with casual games. Or a distraction of sorts to finish or continue playing the game is not a problem at all."
,Recommended,230050,3211114,"Posted: 30 March, 2013",all,Hairbautt,"DLC Quest is a cute satirical platformer that pokes fun at use of downloadable content (DLC) by the gaming industry. The gameplay is what you would expect from a side-scroller, but the main objective is to collect coins in order to purchase in-game DLC (real money not needed). It is a fun way to progress and the dialogue is cleverly utilized making up a solid for-fun platformer."
