,Recommended,230050,26049293,"Posted: 15 October, 2016",all,Joraffe,Yo they made DLC fun.
,Recommended,230050,10988775,"Posted: 30 June, 2014",all,Captain MooMoos,"This is a long review so if you just want a brief summary of why I recommend DLC Quest then skip toResultsand read from there.Going Loud Studious creates the perfect satire that really displays how the game industry has changed over the years. DLC Quest offers fun RPG that continually makes you laugh by showing you what is wrong with gaming companies.Story:The adventure begins as Player arises within the middle of 2D world. Only able to more right he must find currency that represents real money to buy DLC that unlocks all the basics the game didn’t come with. The princess has been kidnapped and it is up to Player to go and save her from a bad guy, who is like a wizard.Campaign:There is no difficulty for this game, in fact there is essentially no combat, and you can’t die. Yet you will continually fight on to collect as many coins as possible. You will meet NPCs that provide you with little to no information, and will continually joke about their purpose. As you progress through the game you will unlock DLC that is required to complete the game, and even have the option to buy DLC that just jazzes it up. The campaign isn’t very long, but it keeps you gripped and there are many little secrets that make you want to keep playing.Gameplay:This game gives you a weapon, and the ability to move and jump. You will essentially be running around collecting coins the entire game. There will essentially be no combat, and no reason you should die. In fact the game is a huge waste of time, but it’s hilarious and you will play it anyway. The game is simple and the mechanics are basic, but what makes this game unique is that every little aspect must be purchased with the in game currency. Don’t worry you won’t actually spend any real money as you will find the required currency to purchase the upgrades throughout the levels.Live Freemium or Die Hard:Funnily a game called DLC quest actually has no DLC. The second campaign is free and it includes all new levels and even the ability to die. There are traps and even some fights which pose all new challenges to the story. The game offers all new puzzles, abilities, jokes, and DLC that make for a riot. It’s definitely worth checking out, even if it’s not DLC.Results:This game is reasonably priced at about $2.99; realistically you will probably play this game for 2-hours so it’s about $1.50 an hour if you want to look at it like that. The campaign is witty and gives a new look to how the gaming industry has changed over the years. DLC Quest sheds a light on how most games today offer DLC that should be included with the initial product. It includes funny jokes, interesting level design, and a simple story that makes you want to actually beet the game. If you like simple platformers and enjoy finding secrets then DLC Quest is the game for you. I would recommend this game, especially if it is on sale.Pros:+Simple game mechanics+Two campaigns+Lots of DLC (none of which you actually pay money for)+Funny dialogue and game design+Amazing story (Where is the princess? What happened to all the villagers?)+You can totally complete the Grindstone without using the DLC XP Boost. You even get a special message for doing it, but no achievement.Cons:-Not as much DLC as promised (I want to give them real money so I can unlock a jetpack horse)-On Live Freemium or Die Hard if you buy all the DLC you may find yourself stuck at the last section (as there are only enough coins to barely get you through the campaign)."
