,Recommended,230050,11374834,"Posted: 23 July, 2014",all,Olde,"I really enjoyed DLC Quest. It's fun to play, has a charming atmosphere, and is quite humorous in poking fun at lots of cliches and tropes of the video game industry. At its core, it's a simple, comedic sidescroller with an ostensibly generic storyline, yet it never hesitates to point out its own irrational logic, from its cliched characters to the seemingly bizarre aspects that are currently part of today's gaming industry.The premise behind DLC Quest is that a bad guy captures a princess, so obviously it's your job to stop him and rescue the damsel in distress. Heard this story a million times before? So have the developers at Going Loud Studios, so what they've done is put their own spin on this age-old premise. Your task is to first collect enough coins to buy DLC within the game world itself. A clear commentary on the cash-grubbing nature of the video game industry, these little packs are initially required in order for you to do the most basic actions, such as moving both left AND right and being able to pause the game. As you progress, the game gives you some nice aesthetic features as well as weapons/items.I was surprised at how good the control is. The jumping mechanic feels like the original Super Mario Bros. (where you can control height and momentum in the air), which I appreciate immensely. You move left and right at a reasonable pace, too. The controls are customizable and the graphics are vibrant and appealing. Aesthetically, the game's design gives it an NES feel. The dialogue is often funny, with characters acknowledging their ridiculous requests or their arbitrary roles in making you run off and do stuff with no justification other than that's how these games work. DLC Quest on a whole is very tongue-in-cheek that way. That being said, there were a couple things that I thought could be improved. To progress through the game, you obviously need to get enough coins to purchase certain DLC items, but a couple of times I couldn't figure out where to go, because I thought I had cleared out all the areas. Turns out there are some secret areas you have to look for where the walls are missing their borders, which are easy to miss. There are also some areas that you might not realize you can get to for similar reasons (boulders or bushes obscured by the foreground, etc.). Otherwise, I found the platforming to be relatively easy, simple enough for an old fogey like me to get through.Overall, I think DLC Quest is a very creative, imaginative, quirky, charming, humorous game well worth its price point. It pokes fun at itself and other gaming cliches, but even though it admits its own ""faults,"" it still kept me wanting to play. If you're at all into sidescrollers, I'd recommend giving this one a try."
,Recommended,230050,9039615,"Posted: 9 February, 2014",all,Skiru,EA Games has been revealed!
,Recommended,230050,12844108,"Posted: 8 November, 2014",all,[Y4L]EanLicksBigDick,i loved the idea of this game. and theres tons more you can do with it..
,Recommended,230050,16369676,"Posted: 13 June, 2015",all,Harley,"Unlock Review Section Titles: 5 coinsWhat is happening to the gaming industry? We live in an age of almost circular mistrust and exploitation. With piracy and second hand sales apparently ever increasing and a CONTINUAL drain on the potential earnings of game studios, it's time for them to hit back. And they do this with DOWNLOADABLE content.DOWNLOADABLE content is the scourge of the consumer, a desperate grab for more money from the creators. We know you bought your game, but pay more! Pay more to see the ending, to see the plots, to improve your power... Pay more to complete your experience!Okay, that might be slightly unbalanced (and not representative of my actual views, that's for another time), but it was only an introduction. It is hardly going to be news to anyone that some of the practices creeping in to gaming are unpopular, or at best divisive. There are some thoughts that, with the birth of microtransactions and freemium set-ups, we are heading toward some sort of dystopian future for games.That's where DLC Quest comes in! An indie developed 2D platformer which pretty much bases itself in this vision of the future of gaming, where anything you could possibly want in a game comes...as an extra!Of course, this doesn't mean that the game becomes extortionately expensive, as this is done with tongue planted firmly within the cheek. It serves to ridicule not only the poor practices that are heading this slippery slope, but also other parts of the general gaming world.DLC Quest offers two separate, but linked, campaigns – DLC Quest and Live Freemium or Die, which are both provided in the package. Fortunately, the developers obviously resisted the urge to forge a bond with the ironic and hypocritical by making Live Freemium or Die into paid downloadable content.So what's the context behind the parody? Well, in DLC Quest, the player takes control of Player, a sprite-come-hero that is dragged into the the perils of the village, aided in his various quests by the magnanimous shopkeeper offering all sorts of goodies that are necessary for defeating the bad guy and saving the princess and all of the other gaming clichés you can think of. It must be said that DLC Quest is very short and to the point, with some (but not a lot) of exploration to be done before even 100% completion.Live Freemium or Die is a “direct sequel” of sorts to DLC Quest, and provides a much more fleshed out experience than that of the former. Continuing the rather contrived storyline to this point of DLC Quest, Live Freemium or Die CONTINUES following Player as he investigates a recent string of related deaths in the village, providing a much larger scale of map for exploration and a slightly more directed story than the first part of the duology.Gameplay-wise, the DLC duo doesn't really do anything to innovate, nor does it do anything particularly wrong. The game plays as a fairly simple 2D platformer, with each game providing a slightly different platforming mechanic to get around with. It must also be noted that Live Freemium or Die adds a little more of the challenge that DLC Quest was pretty much devoid of. That being said, it's hardly Super Meat Boy and won't provide too much of a headache to anyone. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, as it allows many people to enjoy the concept and humour within, but don't come in expecting to be tested.So if DLC Quest isn't going to win awards for its gameplay, what about the graphics and sounds? Well, once you've unlocked the audio and visual packs, it can be seen that it is a fairly basic affair. The 8-bit visual style pays good homage to the early days of gaming history, whilst the fairly catchy (albeit short, much like the game) chiptune background music also adds to the aesthetic. These provide a great contrast to the issues of modern and future gaming models that the game attempts to address.So, if you're wanting a AAA blockbuster that's going to provide you with hours of content and the complexities that come with it, then you are looking in the wrong place. If you're wanting a technical masterpiece or keyboard smashing difficulty, then your experience is not here. If, however, you are looking for a short and simple distraction, at only a fraction of the PRICE of a map pack, with plenty of satirical amusement (As such, it could be described as a much more concise version of what Duke Nukem Forever tried to be), then look no further than DLC Quest – and be happy that the industry haven't quite plunged to the depths that the game attests to!Unlock Final Review Score Pack: 8 coins"
76561198067888927,Not Recommended,230050,7801415,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,Epic Lad,"I bought DLC quest because I like the statement it makes about the directon the gaming industry seems  to be heading. I wanted to support anything that openly mocks the shady techniques publishers have started using to slowly and steadily squeeze each penny out of their customers. The game had a few classic references to cyber-hardships many gamers would remember. In fact, some of the gameplay was intriguing and really struck home. However, the game seemed to be lacking something. Collecting coins is primarily the bulk of your gameplay and that got old quick.Even for the low price I paid, two hours is too short and the game could use some more variety (maybe some mini-games?). By the time you get into the game it either ends or the humor gets a little stale. I wont miss the cash but I regret the two hours I invested in this game."
