,Not Recommended,230050,14602204,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,Wrath,"I've thought about this for significantly longer than this game deserves and have come up with a couple of conclusions on what I think of it.You're just not going to get Upton Sinclair's The Jungle in the 21st century, certainly not some type of work that makes people reevaluate what they're doing, what they're giving, and what they're getting in return. So a satirical game like this with seemingly good intentions, created to poke fun at a poor industry practice is likely the only way to make a strong political statement, at least one that gets any attention. The fact that DLC Quest came from Greenlight makes it all the better.However, I'm not recommending this game for several reasons.  The primary reason is that it's just not very good. Gameplay is very Super Mario Bros: Sidescroller, very rudimentary exploration, spend most of your time collecting coins, there's something about a princess. Part of the impact of the satire is more or less aimed at this similarity. There's an unspoken message that says, essentially, ""imagine this is the late 80s, early 90s and you can't even have sound because Mario was made by Ubisoft"". That's an amusing concept on paper and an arguably effective way to make your statement, but it's not all that enjoyable to experience.Quests in this game have to live within that Mario framework, balance simplicity, but also try to tell a basic story that further supports the dev's point. The result is endless hide and seek coin collecting and busywork tasks that prolong the time you have to play the game and delay the hour you'll put it down. Yeah, that's basically what all quests in all games do, but they're typically more interesting an involved than ""travel to the other side of the map and press E. Travel to the other side of the map again and press E."" When the top two rarest achievements in the game are ""do the entire thing again - but faster!"", you get an idea of what you're getting into. Ultimately, there are two ends you can reach with this playstyle. The first is that the dev doesn't know what quests are or how to make enjoyable ""meat and potatoes"" content for a game (which is likely), or the dev is making a larger statement that 90% of real life is collecting coins and busy work (which is naïve - look, I have time to both play this gameandcriticize it! :P).One other reason that I'm not much of a fan of it is that this is marketed as a full-fledged video game. In 1985, if it wasn't a satire game and had different theming altogether, it would still be decidedly short on content. You can finish this in two to three hours. Today, it's easy to make a game of this quality and spam them out on the internet. This is how Miniclip and other flash game websites are alive.Now, with that in mind, I'm going to list some of the top-rated reviews for this game:""You can buy more DLC than Borderlands 2 has. 10/10"" - Hammercorps""Download the Review DLC to access this review."" -GmCity""Had to spend extra to pause the game. 10/10"" - Fatal'z NutzThat's it. Those aren’t snippets, those are the full reviews. Indicated by the fact that these, among others,aretop reviews, the basic atmosphere of DLC Quest feedback is basically ""I agree with this game's premise"" and ""Gosh, I don't know, I just like it"". This is actually not far removed from how DLC, itself, is marketable. Notwithstanding publishers that pride themselves on actual expansions to a game, which introduces 30-50% of the initial content they originally didn't intent on developing, let's take more rampant publishers as an example.Let's take a game like Crusader Kings II, published by Paradox Interactive, which is a lovely game by the way, although it suffers from rampant DLC release. As of February 2015, there are 52 DLC items which includes four major additions, two ebooks (of all things) seven music additions, and 39 glorified reskins of ruler clothes or soldier uniforms. Why do people purchase these things? Basically, for the same reason behind the reviews for DLC Quest. They agree with the premise of the original game...plus a healthy mix of ""I just feel empty inside without it"".So really, by marketing a flash game as a full fledged video game, at a DLC price, with a satirical premise, Going Loud has actually (rather impressively) created a game that functions as DLC normally would. As a result, they've published very little content, but to an extraordinary amount of profit."
,Recommended,230050,10791397,"Posted: 25 June, 2014",all,Yerakor,"I feel like they are trying to Troll me and Confuse me alot, in which they are successing! This is a game that is short and fun, overall a great game when you have some spare Time on a Trip. I mean for a Trip, because you can save easily and its portable for Mac and Windows!"
,Recommended,230050,19276862,"Posted: 25 November, 2015",all,Goofy,"DLC QuestGenre:PlatformerDescription:The game's emphasis is on upgrading, using satire to parodize modern games that require DLC and microtransactions to enjoy fully by making simple mechanics cost in-game coins. Other than that, it is a simple platformer, with some occasional combat that consists of mashing a button to kill an enemy. There are secrets in the game such as places where you can walk through the wall and gain extra coins. There is also a selection of achievements that enhance the game by adding objectives. Overall it was worth the few dollars I spent on it: a simple platformer with a twist. The one problem I had is that it's extremely short; I was lucky to even get a few hours in it, as most playthroughs seem to take anywhere from 30 minutes to an hour. It's short but sweet."
