76561198063241796,Recommended,230050,9313464,"Posted: 1 March, 2014",all,Kimhari_NO_PASS,NEW DLC! Customer Review by Kimhari_No_Pass!Spend 10 Coins to unlock this review. This splendidly written review concerns the game 'DLC Quest' and endorses the game for its sardonic humour and casual gameplay.There are no refunds on this DLC.
,Recommended,230050,18303310,"Posted: 3 October, 2015",all,Foxysen,"DLC Quest is a short parody platformer game released in 2011 on both PC and Xbox 360 service, made by Going Loud Studios. It would then get an expansion pack ""Live Freemium or Die"" in 2013 for both platforms. Which was free for PC, but sold on Xbox 360, probably because of Microsoft policy. Because you know, they dislike hosting free stuff on their servers, as you heard being the reason why Valve wasn't updating Team Fortress 2 for Xbox 360. Anyway, I think that this also came to Steam only in 2013 as well. Yep, expansion pack / sequel included, no worries.And well, as you see, it's a simple platformer, that parodies everything DLC and modern. And you have to purchase DLC through in-game money in in-game shop, which after a while may start to look no different from what you do in normal games. Hm, maybe it could be more funny if they actually sold DLC as DLC for the game for extremely low-low price of one cent or such? But nah.You know how it goes with most joke games: people say 10/10 for the premise but others start to hate them by the time they beat them. Such joke games must know boundaries and know when to end, as well as trying not to enrage people too much. Thankfully, DLC Quest knows them and ends when it should. It does seem short, but at least it kept fresh enough until the end and was enjoyable.Not to mentioning that game is enjoyable by itself for a very short time that it playes. You just explore small map, find some curious stuff, collect money, platforming is responsible and easy. Original DLC Quest campaign doesn't allow you to die and is shortest. Live Freemium and Die adds some challenge to keep players enganged after original, mostly by adding spikes that will kill and send you back to checkpoint. But they are still pleasent and nothing compared to flood of indie ""hard platformers for sake of hard"".So yea, game looks pretty enough with some 8-bit-like music that is enjoyable and doesn't try to do a horrible joke. It also makes you question many life-important things. Like, why Season Pass is called Season Pass? No, seriously. Or how much developers went insane with tiny DLCes. Even though you all probably just wait until game goes on huge sale where you buy bundle with all DLCs for dirt cheap anyway.But yes, it doesn't overstay the welcome and has enjoyable simple platforming, so you can spend a hour or two on it. Unless you try to do two hidden hardcore speedrun achievements or try to beat scores.Just try to get it while it's on sale. Not because game costs too much. Doesn't matter what discount. You just should be able to tell yourself that you got it during your crazy Steam sales impulses. Instead of asking yourself why you went so low into rabbit hole that you are fully purchasing joke games based on their premise and give them 10/10, while you could get some better proper game instead.AND HEY, ZOMBIE DLC!"
