,Not Recommended,230050,12709854,"Posted: 31 October, 2014",all,zaki,"A very good idea executed in a disappointingly mediocre way. The initial hook is simply brilliant: everything is a DLC. From moving left to animations to jump and so on. The problem is, there really is no ""and so on"", it's an extremely short game and you can feel the creators have run out of ideas very quickly into the game. It doesn't take an hour to complete everything in the game - if at this point we can even call it that. Now, it is possible that this is only a segue into the next episode (undoubtedly coming as a DLC), but while I really applaud the developers for putting in the effort to create a game and hope they will continue to work on games in the future, at the same time I can't recommend it because when it comes to DLC Quest, they didn't really put in all the effort needed to create a game."
,Recommended,230050,1547311,"Posted: 27 July, 2013",all,noibn,"DLC Quest is a short game whose raison-d'etre is to satirize all the DLC practices you love to hate, along with a variety of other negative aspects of today's gaming world. The game features two main quests - the original DLC Quest, and a ""sequel"" titled ""Live Freemium or Die"". Each quest clocks in at around 1 hour or so (assuming you complete them at or near 100%). Gameplay is typical 2D platformer style. All you do is run around, jumping and collecting coins, which are then used to purchase ""DLC"" (missing game features that, when reinstated, allow you to continue progressing). You basically just repeat that cycle for an hour and you're done. The game itself is really easy, so this isn't really something you'll want to play for a challenge. Rather, it's all about the humor and satire. So how is it in those terms? Pretty decent, actually. Some of the writing is a tad heavy-handed, especially near the beginning, but overall I found it to be pretty well done, and even laugh-out-loud funny at times (well, maybe more like 'chuckle-out loud')... anyways, I guess my point is that the game got right what it needed to get right. It's hardly a challenge as a game, but the 2 hours spent playing does provide some interesting moments that you probably won't find anywhere else. If you're up for an experimental experience, and don't mind taking a chance at the low price tag, I say go for it. Just don't buy it expecting anything more than an interactive satire/spoof."
