76561197998159333,Recommended,230050,1799860,"Posted: 31 July, 2013",all,Raveneer,"DLC Quest takes the concept of DLC and skewers it with satire. While it is a short game (complete with speedrun achievements), it packs a fair amount of platforming fun into its two short campaigns, DLC Quest and Life Freemium or Die. In both, you must (eventually with the requisite DLC) jump and explore the nooks and cranies of the world to find coins to purchase DLC. There is a bit of Metroidvania imbedded here and it displays it proudly with its solid platforming mechanics.There is a light story to each of the main quests: in one you must save Princess Macguffin from Bad Guy, and in the sequel you must save the villagers from a rampaging monster. Really, they're both flimsy and funny excuses for you to run around and collect coins for DLC.  Combat does not exist aside from a few sequences, and death only visits your character upon touching spiked pit traps. While Super Meat Boy it is not, the platforming is challenging enough for die hard completionists and speedrunners to enjoy.The game doesn't have much lasting appeal unless you want to hunt down every missing coin or you have a burning desire to tackle the speed runs. That said, for its low price,  DLC Quest will offer a fun look at what happens when DLC goes too far."
,Not Recommended,230050,8064025,"Posted: 15 December, 2013",all,Blacksmith.13,"I would recommend this game as it is fun and can kill time, but I have landed on not simply because there isn't any replayability from the original game or the freemium DLC that it comes with. If you plan on getting this game, expect to be finished in under three hours and not play it again until something new comes out for it. For the price, it is decent, but again, it could be more in-depth."
