,Recommended,230050,12267561,"Posted: 27 September, 2014",all,OrangeyChocolate,"What's it about?DLC Quest is a simple sidescrolling platformer that pokes fun at the videogames industry, as well as gaming tropes and gamers themselves.How does it play?The game, as mentioned before, is a simple Metroidvania-style platformer in which you purchase ""DLC packs"" from the shopkeeper (with coins you pick up in-game, not real money) to gain new abilities in order to explore more of the game world. There are also DLC packs that simply add stupid things to the game, like putting all the NPCs in bikinis. The controls are tight and accurate, and you can play with either the keyboard or a controller. I used my Xbox 360 controller,  since I prefer to play platformers with it, and it proved to be very comfortable since the game doesn't use very many buttons and using the control stick for movement felt more natural.The game is split into two parts. The first part is a very simple, basic adventure with barely any challenge at all. It is exclusively a vehicle in which to carry the game's cutting satire about the games industry. The second part, ""Live Freemium or Die"", is an expanded adventure that offers more challenge (though not much), more jokes and more DLC packs, along with some NPC characters based on famous personalities in the gaming world. This second section is excellent; it makes the already amusing game much more interesting while maintaining the high quality of the writing and humour.How does it look?DLC Quest uses simple 8-bit pixel art style graphics with a straightforward background. The art style is charming and, because of its simplicity, it runs very smoothly with no slowdown to speak of. You could probably play this on an Apple Macbook with no trouble at all (I used to play on Macbook, so I know the pain...).How does it sound?The music in this game is actually pretty good. There are different themes depending on which zone you are in, as you might expect, and the sound effects are very much in vein of classic NES and SNES games.Long story shortDLC Quest is a very unique and entertaining little game. It's both a solid platforming adventure and a piece of satire greater than any Youtube pap. It's very short (I finished both stories in less than two hours), which may put off some so-called ""core"" gamers, but the injokes around every corner kept me smiling and laughing all the way. For the satire alone this game is worth the price. And it's a very good price: DLC Quest is going for £1.99 (or your regional equivalent) right now. I think that's a steal for a game this good.Good PointsCutting satire and spot-on writingGameplay is solid and enjoyableCharming art styleGood musicBad PointsVery shortHardly challenging at allRedWolf Rating: 7/10 - Good"
