,Recommended,230050,8385314,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,Grey Area,"A bite-sized chunk of satire, DLC Quest will make you laugh, question the state of the industry... and then cry a bit (in that order).The author pokes fun at most of today's trends in a very thoughtful and engaging way - from filler NPCs to ""necessary"" zombies, nothing is left untouched! Of course, as the title implies, the main focus is acquiring DLCs - this is accomplished by platforming and obtaining coins, then visiting the friendly shopkeeper. Everything from background music to the character animations is initially locked, so you have to work a bit before everything falls into place and you can finally start advancing the ""story"". Luckily, the progression is perfect and the platforming decent, with a nostalgic, retro feel. Controls feel responsive, the secrets are abundant, but keep in mind the platforming is just a means to an end. So, don't expect to be challenged, that's not the point.The game is split up in two parts (the second story was created after launch and is bundled for free and accessible from the main menu):- The originalDLC Questwhich tackles the subject of the landslides of DLCs made available for modern games, the morality of the practice and how we, as both gamers and game protagonists deal with the trend;- A sort of expansion,Live Freemium or Diethat continues the story and deals with other, current industry trends like day one patches, sub-par optimization and so on.Both of these are treated in a satirical manner and placed on an overaching storyline that left me, at least, chuckling.Throughout the game there isn't one moment where the 4th wall is left standing or when the game takes itself seriously (even the achievements and trading cards reflect that). Adding to the absurdity and humor are the NPCs you encounter and the situations you are forced into, all of them tropes from modern gaming trends, executed flawlessly. You fill find yourself saying ""I see what you did there!"" and having a laugh more often than not. If you're into game design, DLC Quest makes for a perfect dissection piece - it's fun and easy to understand how, why and when each mechanic is introduced, the map design, the intended game progression and so on.Overall, it's a funny, entertaining ride; a discourse on the modern gaming industry, a mirror for both it and ourselves to look into.Saying more or going into detail would spoil the experience, so you own it to yourself to try it out. Even though there's not much replay value it doesn't overstay its welcome, nor recycle its ideas - each DLC, NPC, line of dialogue or encounter reflects something very specific and it's up to you to recognize and understand what... and why. It will give as much as you are willing to put into it.The fact that it approaches a mature and so-close-to-home subject in such a hilarious way, all the while sparking dialogue and introspection is worth the entry price alone."
,Recommended,230050,4387986,"Posted: 3 July, 2013",all,Inquisitor Reira,"A seriously great game, especially for those who are angered by the current money grabbing game economy. A lot funnier than I thought, despite some jokes making me cringe.Worth a buy! 8/10"
